    <Table CellSpacing="5">
      <TableRowGroup>
        <TableRow>
          <TableCell>
            <Paragraph FontSize="22"><Run>How to: Create an Expander</Run>

            </Paragraph>

          </TableCell>

        </TableRow>

      </TableRowGroup>

    </Table>

    <Paragraph>This example shows how to create an Expander control. An <Run FontWeight="Bold">Expander</Run>
 control enables users to view a header that expands to display more content or collapses to save space.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22">Example
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph>The following example creates an <Run FontWeight="Bold">Expander</Run>
 control that opens downward and displays text that is defined by the Content property. The Header property defines the <Run FontWeight="Bold">Expander</Run>
 title, which in this example is <Run>My Expander</Run>
. 
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph>The <Run FontWeight="Bold">Expander</Run>
 control window is open when the application starts because the IsExpanded property is set to <Run FontWeight="Bold">true</Run>
.
    </Paragraph>

    <Table CellSpacing="5">
      <TableRowGroup>
        <TableRow>
          <TableCell>
            <Paragraph FontSize="22"><Run>XAML </Run>

            </Paragraph>

          </TableCell>

        </TableRow>

        <TableRow>
          <TableCell>
            <Paragraph xml:space="preserve" TextAlignment="Left" FontSize="8pt" FontFamily="Courier New"><Run>
&lt;Expander Name="myExpander" Background="Tan" HorizontalAlignment="Left" Header="My Expander" ExpandDirection="Down" IsExpanded="True" Width="100"> 
&lt;TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap"> Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipisicing elit, sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt ut labore et dolore magna aliqua 
&lt;/TextBlock> 
&lt;/Expander> </Run>

            </Paragraph>

          </TableCell>

        </TableRow>

      </TableRowGroup>

    </Table>

